channel.title: Project Edge-PKz [24/7]
channel.description:
[size=40pt]ONLINE 24/7[/size] [img]http://img213.imageshack.us/img213/209/rsedreku1.jpg[/img] http://uppit.com/KUX7OP <---- client
I Started new project and it's being deveploved really hard by me. Im hoping i can get divine to deveplove it with me ,because we are the ones that made the 2 best servers when demonik v2 was released.
This server will have following things: Mostly made for low level F2P Pure pking;You can only be 3-60 level combat. Shops that include following items;Ranged Supplies,Sword Shop,Armour shop. and the Apothecary to get strength potions, Apothecary can sell you Strength potions for 3k each ,but if you collect red spider eggs and give him 50gp he will make one for you,This brings the feeling of getting pots by yourself and still keep economy.
There will be monsters that drop rune items, Not too hard but not too easy too...I've been thinking to put following stats to it: 75HP,70 Defence,50 Strength,45 Attack. You dont hit so much to it,but it doesnt hit back too hard either,and it takes while to kill. These monsters will be/not be in wilderness ,its your choice.
Lobsters,Tuna,Swordfishes will be fished by yourself, Im moving the fishing spots into Edgeville,so you wont have to walk so much.
You start with Iron 2-H,Strength ammy,Sleeping bag,25minds ,15 airs, 10 waters,10 earths.
There's NPC to get rewards for pking, Each time you kill someone you get a point,when you die ,you lose a point. This makes us to care about being pked.
Here's the list of rewards: 1 Kill - 10k 10 kills - 100k 50 kills - 500k 100 kills - Santa's Hat.
Santa's hat prize will be around 1 million.
Divine ,contact me on msn : nurmilaukaus@hotmail.com.[img]http://[/img][img]http://[/img][img]http://[/img][img]http://[/img][img]http://[/img][img]http://[/img][img][/img]

item.dc:creator: @propker propker
item.description:
@propker wrote:

The host edgepkz.sytes.net has been disabled.
The requested page you tried accessing was involved in a Fraudulent Phishing scheme.

The ultimate goal of a phishing scheme is to gather customer information such as usernames, passwords, social security numbers, and credit card numbers. The main way they do this and probably how you reached this site is through spoofed email. The email claims to be from a website or company asking for you to login or provide them with some other confidential information.
Tips to protect yourself from fraud

*

  If you get an email or pop-up message that asks for personal or financial information, do not reply or click on the link in the message. Legitimate companies don't ask for this information via email. If you are concerned about your account, contact the organization in the email using a telephone number you know to be genuine, or open a new Internet browser session and type in the company's correct Web address. In any case, don't cut and paste the link in the message.
*

  Don't email personal or financial information. Email is not a secure method of transmitting personal information. If you initiate a transaction and want to provide your personal or financial information through an organization's Web site, look for indicators that the site is secure, like a lock icon on the browser's status bar or a URL for a website that begins "https:" (the "s" stands for "secure"). Unfortunately, no indicator is foolproof; some phishers have forged security icons.
*

  Review credit card and bank account statements as soon as you receive them to determine whether there are any unauthorized charges. If your statement is late by more than a couple of days, call your credit card company or bank to confirm your billing address and account balances.
*

  Be cautious about opening any attachment]or downloading any files from emails you receive, regardless of who sent them.
*

  Use anti-virus software and keep it up to date. Some phishing emails contain software that can harm your computer or track your activities on the Internet without your knowledge. Anti-virus software and a firewall can protect you from inadvertently accepting such unwanted files. Anti-virus software scans incoming communications for troublesome files. Look for anti-virus software that recognizes current viruses as well as older ones; that can effectively reverse the damage; and that updates automatically.
*

  Report suspicious activity to the FTC. If you get spam that is phishing for information, forward it to spam@uce.gov. If you believe you've been scammed, file your complaint at www.ftc.gov, and then visit the FTC's Identity Theft Web site at www.consumer.gov/idtheft to learn how to minimize your risk of damage from ID theft. Visit www.ftc.gov/spam to learn other ways to avoid email scams and deal with deceptive spam.
